{"title_page": "Palantir Technologies", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Palantir Technologies Inc.\n| logo = Palantir company logo.png\n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| products = {{plainlist|\n*Palantir Gotham\n*Palantir Foundry}}\n| num_employees = {{increase}}2,500 (October 2019)<ref>{{cite news |first=Quentin |last=Hardy |date=May 31, 2014 |title = Unlocking Secrets, if Not Its Own Value |work = [[The New York Times]] |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/01/business/unlocking-secrets-if-not-its-own-value.html |accessdate = 2015-01-19}}</ref><ref name=20billion/>\n| foundation = {{start date and age|2003}}\n| founders = [[Peter Thiel]]<br>Nathan Gettings<br>[[Joe Lonsdale]]<br>[[Stephen Cohen (entrepreneur)|Stephen Cohen]]<br>[[Alex Karp]]\n| key_people = {{plainlist|\n*Peter Thiel ([[Chairman]])\n*Alex Karp ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])}}\n| location_city = [[Palo Alto, California]], US\n| revenue = $739 million (2019)<ref>{{cite news |title = Palantir revenue |work = Craft |url = https://www.businessinsider.com/palantir-1-billion-revenue-2020-ipo-2020-4|accessdate = 2019-11-20}}</ref>\n| homepage = {{url|http://www.palantir.com/}}\n}}\n'''Palantir Technologies''' is a [[privately held company|private]] American software company that specializes in [[big data]] [[analytics]]. Headquartered in [[Palo Alto, California]], it was founded by [[Peter Thiel]], Nathan Gettings, [[Joe Lonsdale]], [[Stephen Cohen (entrepreneur)|Stephen Cohen]], and [[Alex Karp]]. The company's name is derived from ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]'': a ''[[palant\u00edr]]'' is an artifact used to communicate with or see faraway parts of the world.\n\nThe company is known for three projects in particular: Palantir Gotham, Palantir Metropolis and Palantir Foundry. Palantir Gotham is used by [[counter-terrorism]] analysts at offices in the [[United States Intelligence Community]] (USIC) and [[United States Department of Defense]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-25/peter-thiel-s-palantir-wins-role-in-823-million-government-contract|title=Peter Thiel\u2019s Palantir Wins Role in $823 Million Government Contract|date=2020-02-25|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2020-03-18|language=en}}</ref>, fraud investigators at the [[Recovery Accountability and Transparency Board]], and cyber analysts at [[Information Warfare Monitor]], while Palantir Metropolis is used by [[Hedge fund|hedge funds]], banks, and financial services firms.<ref name=\"bare_url\" /><ref name=\"npr\" /> Palantir Foundry is used by corporate clients such as Morgan Stanley, Merck KGaA, Airbus, and Fiat Chrysler Automobiles NV.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=b07a6000-3595-11e9-8c0f-aba472ef73fe&url=L25ld3MvYXJ0aWNsZXMvMjAxOS0wMS0xNi9wYWxhbnRpci1wb3N0ZWQtbmVhcmx5LTEtYmlsbGlvbi1pbi0yMDE4LXNhbGVzLWV4ZWN1dGl2ZS1zYXlz|title=Bloomberg - Are you a robot?|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2019-02-21}}</ref> Palantir's original clients were federal agencies of the USIC. It has since expanded its customer base to serve state and local governments, as well as private companies in the financial and healthcare industries.<ref name=\"historypalantir\"/> Karp, Palantir's [[chief executive officer]], announced in 2013 that the company would not pursue an [[IPO]], as going public would make \"running a company like ours very difficult\".<ref name=\"teafunding\"/> However, on October 18, 2018, the [[Wall Street Journal]] reported that Palantir was considering an IPO in the first half of 2019 following a $41 billion valuation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/secretive-data-company-palantir-weighs-giant-public-offering-1539864003|title=Secretive Data Company Palantir Weighs Giant Public Offering|last=Copeland|first=Rob|date=2018-10-18|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2018-10-19|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\nThe company was valued at $9 billion in early 2014, with ''[[Forbes]]'' stating that the valuation made Palantir \"among [[Silicon Valley]]'s most valuable private technology companies\".<ref name=\"teafunding\"/> As of December 2014, Thiel was Palantir's largest shareholder.<ref name=\"teafunding\"/> In January 2015, the company was valued at $15 billion after an undisclosed round of funding with $50 million in November 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|title = SEC FORM D |url = https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1321655/000132165514000005/xslFormDX01/primary_doc.xml |publisher=[[Securities and Exchange Commission]] |accessdate = 2015-05-31}}</ref> This valuation rose to $20 billion in late 2015 as the company closed an $880 million round of funding.<ref name=20billion>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/12/23/palantir-has-raised-880-million-at-a-20-billion-valuation/|title=Palantir Has Raised $880 Million At A $20 Billion Valuation|first=Sarah|last=Buhr|website=[[TechCrunch]]|date=December 23, 2015}}</ref> Palantir has never reported a profit. In 2018, [[Morgan Stanley]] valued the company at $6 billion.<ref>{{cite web|title=Palantir Knows Everything About You|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/features/2018-palantir-peter-thiel/?ncid=newsltushpmgnews__TheMorningEmail__042018|website=Bloomberg|accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n===2003\u20132008: Founding and early years===\n[[File:Peter Thiel TechCrunch50.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Founder and chairman [[Peter Thiel]] was Palantir's largest shareholder as of late 2014.]]\nThough usually listed as having been founded in 2004, [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission|SEC]] filings state Palantir's official incorporation to be in May 2003 by [[Peter Thiel]] (co-founder of [[PayPal]]), who named the start-up after the \"[[Palant\u00edr|seeing stone]]\" in [[Tolkien's legendarium]].<ref name=\"historypalantir\">{{cite web |title=A (Pretty) Complete History of Palantir |publisher=Maus Strategic Consulting |url=http://www.mausstrategicconsulting.com/1/post/2014/04/a-pretty-complete-history-of-palantir.html |date=April 2014 |archivedate=16 May 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140516035733/http://www.mausstrategicconsulting.com/1/post/2014/04/a-pretty-complete-history-of-palantir.html |url-status=dead}}</ref> Thiel saw Palantir as a \"mission-oriented company\" which could apply software similar to PayPal's fraud recognition systems to \"reduce terrorism while preserving civil liberties.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Greenberg|first1=Andy|last2=Mac|first2=Ryan|title=How A 'Deviant' Philosopher Built Palantir, A CIA-Funded Data-Mining Juggernaut|website=Forbes|date=August 14, 2013|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andygreenberg/2013/08/14/agent-of-intelligence-how-a-deviant-philosopher-built-palantir-a-cia-funded-data-mining-juggernaut/}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Thiel bankrolled the creation of a prototype by PayPal engineer Nathan Gettings and [[Stanford University]] students [[Joe Lonsdale]] and [[Stephen Cohen (entrepreneur)|Stephen Cohen]]. That same year, Thiel hired [[Alex Karp]], a former colleague of his from [[Stanford Law School]], as [[chief executive officer]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://media.palantirtech.com/videos/charlierose.html |title=charlierose |publisher= Media.palantirtech.com |date= |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.crunchbase.com/company/palantir-technologies |title= Palantir Technologies &#124; CrunchBase Profile |publisher=Crunchbase.com |date= |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref>\n\nHeadquartered in [[Palo Alto, California]], the company initially struggled to find investors. According to Karp, [[Sequoia Capital]] chairman [[Michael Moritz]] doodled through an entire meeting, and a [[Kleiner Perkins]] executive lectured the founders about the inevitable failure of their company.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.palantir.com/contact |title= Contact information}}</ref> The only early investments were $2 million from the U.S. [[Central Intelligence Agency]]'s venture capital arm [[In-Q-Tel]], and $30 million from Thiel himself and his venture capital firm, [[Founders Fund]].<ref name=\"bare_url\">{{cite news| url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB125200842406984303 | work=The Wall Street Journal | title=How Team of Geeks Cracked Spy Trade | first=Siobhan | last=Gorman | date=September 4, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"npr\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=106479613 |title= A Tech Fix For Illegal Government Snooping? |publisher=NPR |date= |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foundersfund.com/palantir.php |title=Palantir |publisher= Founders Fund | accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Evelyn |last=Rusli |url=https://techcrunch.com/2010/06/25/palantir-the-next-billion-dollar-company-raises-90-million/ |title=Palantir: The Next Billion-Dollar Company Raises $90 Million |publisher=TechCrunch |date=2010-06-25 |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref><ref name=\"charlierose\">{{cite web|url=http://www.charlierose.com/guest/view/6717 |title= Alexander Karp |publisher=Charlie Rose |date=2009-08-11 |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref>\n\nPalantir developed its technology by computer scientists and analysts from intelligence agencies over three years, through pilots facilitated by In-Q-Tel.<ref>{{cite web| first =Jeff | last = Widman |url= https://venturebeat.com/2009/06/05/palantir-keeps-it-lean-and-mean-on-five-year-journey-from-zero-to-150-employees/ |title=Palantir keeps it lean and mean on five-year journey from zero to 150 employees | publisher=VentureBeat |date=2009-06-05 |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref><ref name=\"bare_url\" /> The company stated computers alone using [[artificial intelligence]] could not defeat an adaptive adversary. Instead, Palantir proposed using human analysts to explore data from many sources, called [[Intelligence amplification|intelligence augmentation]].<ref>{{cite web| first =Ari | last = Gesher |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120414224548/http://blog.palantirtech.com/2010/03/08/friction-in-human-computer-symbiosis-kasparov-on-chess/ |title= Friction in Human-Computer Symbiosis: Kasparov on Chess |publisher= Palantir tech |date=2010-03-08 |accessdate= 2012-01-30}}</ref>\n\n===2009: GhostNet and the Shadow Network ===\nIn 2009 and 2010 respectively, [[Information Warfare Monitor]] used Palantir software to uncover the [[GhostNet]] and the [[Shadow Network]]. The GhostNet was a China-based cyber espionage network targeting  1,295 computers in 103 countries, including the [[Dalai Lama]]\u2019s office, a [[NATO]] computer and  various national embassies.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.cnn.com/video/#/video/tech/2009/03/30/vause.china.cyber.espionage.cnn | work=CNN | title= Video}}</ref> The Shadow Network was also a China-based espionage operation that hacked into the Indian security and defense apparatus. Cyber spies stole documents related to Indian security and NATO troop activity in Afghanistan.<ref name=\"bare_url_a\" /><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/29/technology/29spy.html | work=The New York Times | title=Vast Spy System Loots Computers in 103 Countries | first= John | last=Markoff | date=March 29, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===2010\u20132012: Expansion===\nIn April 2010, Palantir announced a partnership with [[Thomson Reuters]] to sell the Palantir Metropolis product as QA Studio.<ref>{{cite news| title=Press release: Thomson Reuters and Palantir Technologies enter exclusive agreement to create next-generation analytics platform for financial clients |url= http://thomsonreuters.com/content/press_room/financial/2010_04_12_palantir_technologies_agreement |date=2010-04-12 |publisher= Thomson Reuters}}</ref>\nOn June 18, 2010, [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Joe Biden]] and [[Office of Management and Budget]] Director [[Peter Orszag]] held a press conference at the White House announcing the success of fighting fraud in the stimulus by the [[Recovery Accountability and Transparency Board]] (RATB).  Biden credited the success to the software, Palantir, being deployed by the federal government.<ref>{{cite web|first=Tim |last=Kauffman | url=http://www.federaltimes.com/article/20100627/AGENCY05/6270306/ |title=The new high-tech weapons against fraud |publisher= Federal Times |date=2010-06-27 |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref>  He announced that the capability will be deployed at other government agencies, starting with [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]] and [[Medicaid]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/theoval/post/2010/06/obama-administration-to-create-do-not-pay-list-to-bar-shady-contractors/1 | newspaper=USA Today | title=Obama administration to create 'do not pay' list to bar shady contractors | date=2010-06-18 | first=Kathy | last=Kiely}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Peter |last=Orszag |url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/omb/blog/10/06/18/Do-Not-Pay-Do-Read-This-Post|title=Do Not Pay? Do Read This Post |publisher=Whitehouse.gov |date=2010-06-18 |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref><ref name=\"bare_url_b\">{{cite news| url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2010/06/01/companies-capitalize-on-open-government |work= Political Ticker blog |first= Eric |last= Kuhn |date= June 1, 2010 | publisher=CNN | title=Companies capitalize on 'open government' |accessdate= September 28, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.palantir.com/2010/05/govcon5-videos-now-available/ |title=Using Palantir with Open Source Data: Finding and Preventing Fraud in Stimulus Spending |publisher=Palantir Technologies |date=2010-05-04}}</ref>\n\nEstimates were $250 million in revenues in 2011.<ref>{{Cite news |title= Palantir, the War on Terror's Secret Weapon: A Silicon Valley startup that collates threats has quietly become indispensable to the U.S. intelligence community |work= Business Week Magazine |date= November 22, 2011 |first1= Ashlee |last1=Vance |first2=Brad |last2=Stone |url= http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/palantir-the-vanguard-of-cyberterror-security-11222011.html |accessdate= September 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2013\u20132016: Additional funding===\n{|class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float: right; margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 0em; font-size: 85%; background:offwhite; color:black; width:30em; max-width: 60%;\" cellspacing=\"5\"\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|\"[As of 2013] the U.S. spy agencies also employed Palantir to connect databases across departments. Before this, most of the databases used by the CIA and FBI were [[Information silo|siloed]], forcing users to search each database individually. Now everything is linked together using Palantir.\"\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|\u2014 [[TechCrunch]] in January 2015<ref name=\"tebtecnchrun\"/>\n|}\nA document leaked to [[TechCrunch]] revealed that Palantir's clients as of 2013 included at least twelve groups within the U.S. government, including the [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]], [[United States Department of Homeland Security|DHS]], [[National Security Agency|NSA]], [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]], [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]], the [[United States Marine Corps|Marine Corps]], the [[United States Air Force|Air Force]], [[United States Special Operations Command|Special Operations Command]], [[West Point]], the [[Joint Improvised-Threat Defeat Organization]] and Allies, the [[Recovery Accountability and Transparency Board]] and the [[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]. However, at the time the [[United States Army]] continued to use its own data analysis tool.<ref name= \"tebtecnchrun\"/> Also, according to [[TechCrunch]], the U.S. spy agencies such as the CIA and FBI were linked for the first time with Palantir software, as their databases had previously been \"[[Information silo|siloed]].\"<ref name= \"tebtecnchrun\" />\n\nIn September 2013, Palantir disclosed over $196 million in funding according to a U.S. [[Securities and Exchange Commission]] filing.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1321655/000132165513000002/xslFormDX01/primary_doc.xml | title = Notice of Exempt Offering of Securities |date= September 27, 2013 | accessdate = September 28, 2013 | publisher = The United States Securities and Exchange Commission}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Cutler|first=Kim-Mai|title=Palantir Is Raising $197M In Growth Capital, SEC Filing Shows |url= https://techcrunch.com/2013/09/27/palantir-197m-sec-filing/|publisher=TechCrunch}}</ref> It was estimated that the company would likely close almost $1 billion in contracts in 2014.<ref>{{cite news | first1 = Andy | last1 = Greenberg | first2 = Ryan | last2 = Mac | title = How A 'Deviant' Philosopher Built Palantir, A CIA-Funded Data-Mining Juggernaut | date = September 2, 2013 | url = https://www.forbes.com/sites/andygreenberg/2013/08/14/agent-of-intelligence-how-a-deviant-philosopher-built-palantir-a-cia-funded-data-mining-juggernaut/ | work = Forbes | accessdate = September 28, 2013}}</ref> CEO [[Alex Karp]] announced in 2013 that the company would not be pursuing an [[IPO]], as going public would make \"running a company like ours very difficult.\"<ref name=\"teafunding\"/> In December 2013, the company began a round of financing, raising around $450 million from private funders.  This raised the company's value to $9 billion, according to ''[[Forbes]]'', with the magazine further explaining that the valuation made Palantir \"among Silicon Valley\u2019s most valuable private technology companies.\"<ref name= \"teafunding\" />\n\nIn December 2014, ''Forbes'' reported that Palantir was looking to raise $400 million in an additional round of financing, after the company filed paperwork with the [[Securities and Exchange Commission]] the month before. The report was based on research by VC Experts.  If completed, ''Forbes'' stated Palantir's funding could reach a total of $1.2 billion.<ref name=\"teafunding\"/> As of December 2014, the company continued to have diverse private funders, [[Kenneth Langone]] and [[Stanley Druckenmiller]], [[In-Q-Tel]] of the CIA,<ref>{{cite news|first= Jonathan |last= Tirone |date=2018-05-08|title=Peter Thiel and Palantir Are at the Heart of the Iran Nuclear Deal|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-05-08/peter-thiel-in-eye-of-iran-storm-as-deadline-looms-for-trump|newspaper=Bloomberg.com|quote=Palantir, which Thiel and his partners built with CIA funding}}</ref> Tiger Global Management, and [[Founders Fund]], which is a venture Firm operated by [[Peter Thiel]], the chairman of Palantir. As of December 2014, Thiel was Palantir's largest shareholder.<ref name=\"teafunding\" />\n\nThe company was valued at $15 billion in November 2014.<ref>{{Citation | date = Jan 16, 2015 | title = Palantir raising more money after tagged with 15 billion valuation | newspaper = The Wall Street Journal | url = https://blogs.wsj.com/digits/2015/01/16/palantir-raising-more-money-after-tagged-with-15-billion-valuation/}}.</ref> In June 2015, Buzzfeed reported the company was raising up to $500 million in new capital at a valuation of $20 billion.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.buzzfeed.com/williamalden/palantir-valued-at-20-billion-in-new-funding-round |title= Palantir Valued At $20 Billion In New Funding Round| first =William | last = Alden|date=June 23, 2015|publisher=[[Buzzfeed]]|accessdate=June 23, 2015}}</ref> By December 2015, it had raised a further $880 million, while the company was still valued at $20 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/12/23/palantir-has-raised-880-million-at-a-20-billion-valuation/|title=Palantir Has Raised $880 Million At A $20 Billion Valuation|date=December 23, 2015|first=Sarah|last=Buhr|publisher=[[TechCrunch]]}}</ref> In February 2016, Palantir bought Kimono Labs, a startup which makes it easy to collect information from public facing websites.\n\nIn August 2016, Palantir acquired [[data visualization]] startup Silk.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Condon|first1=Stephanie|title=Palantir acquires data visualization startup Silk|url=http://www.zdnet.com/article/palantir-acquires-data-visualization-startup-silk/|accessdate=10 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nPalantir, is one of four large technology firms <ref>{{Cite news|last=Kelion|first=Leo|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-52079287|title=NHS turns to big tech to tackle Covid-19 hot spots|date=2020-03-28|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-29|language=en-GB}}</ref>to start working with the NHS on supporting the [[COVID-19]] efforts through the provision of software from Palantir Foundry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://healthtech.blog.gov.uk/2020/03/28/the-power-of-data-in-a-pandemic/|title=The power of data in a pandemic - Technology in the NHS|website=healthtech.blog.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> \n\n== Products ==\n\n=== Palantir Gotham ===\nPalantir Gotham (formerly known as Palantir Government) [[data integration|integrates]] structured and [[unstructured data]], provides search and discovery capabilities, knowledge management, and secure collaboration. The Palantir platform includes the privacy and [[civil liberties]] protections mandated by legal requirements such as those in the [[9/11 Commission Implementation Act of 2004]].  Palantir's [[privacy]] controls purportedly keep investigations focused, as opposed to the expansive [[data mining]] techniques that have drawn criticism from privacy advocates concerned about civil liberties protection. Palantir maintains security tags{{explain|date=May 2016}} at a granular level.<ref name=\"npr\" /><ref name=\"charlierose\" />\n\nPalantir previously ran the site AnalyzeThe.US,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://analyzethe.us |title= AnalyzeThe.US \u2014 Home |work= Web site |publisher= Palantir  |accessdate= September 28, 2013 }}</ref> which allowed potential Palantir customers and affiliates to use Palantir Gotham to perform analysis on publicly available data from [[data.gov]], [[usaspending.gov]], the [[Center for Responsive Politics]]\u2019 Open Secrets Database, and Community Health Data from [[U.S. Department of Health & Human Services|hhs.gov]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fiercehealthcare.com/press-releases/palantir-technologies-showcase-analysis-community-health-data-initiative-forum-harnes |title=Palantir Technologies to Showcase Analysis at the Community Health Data Initiative Forum: Harnessing the Power of Information to |publisher=FierceHealthcare |date=2010-06-02 |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref>\n\n=== Palantir Metropolis ===\nPalantir Metropolis (formerly known as Palantir Finance) was<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-01-07/palantir-is-said-to-hire-salespeople-it-once-mocked-as-ipo-nears|title=Palantir Stops Mocking Salespeople and Starts Hiring Them|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-palantir-sales-ipo-20190107-story.html|title=Palantir once mocked the idea of salespeople. Now it\u2019s hiring them|last=Chapman|first=Lizette|website=latimes.com|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref> software for [[data integration]], [[information management]] and quantitative [[analytics]].  The software connects to commercial, proprietary and [[public data]] sets and discovers trends, relationships and anomalies, including [[predictive analytics]].<ref name=Bloomberg180419Waldman>{{cite news | last1 = Waldman | first1 = Peter | last2 = Chapman | first2 = Lizette | last3 = Robertson | first3 = Jordan | url = https://www.bloomberg.com/features/2018-palantir-peter-thiel/ | title = Peter Thiel\u2019s data-mining company is using War on Terror tools to track American citizens. The scary thing? Palantir is desperate for new customers. | publisher = Bloomberg | date = April 19, 2018 | access-date = April 24, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Bloomberg180419Mak>{{cite news | last = Mak | first = Aaron | title = Report: Palantir Helped JPMorgan Spy on Employees | url = https://slate.com/technology/2018/04/jpmorgan-used-palantir-tools-monitor-employee-activity-bloomberg-report.html | publisher = Bloomberg | date = April 19, 2018 | access-date = April 24, 2018}}</ref> Aided by 120 \"forward-deployed engineers\" of Palantir during 2009, Peter Cavicchia III of JPMorgan used Metropolis to monitor employee communications and alert the insider threat team when an employee showed any signs of potential disgruntlement: the insider alert team would further scrutinize the employee and possibly conduct physical surveillance after hours with bank security personnel.<ref name=Bloomberg180419Waldman/><ref name=Bloomberg180419Mak/> The Metropolis team used emails, download activity, browser histories, and GPS locations from JPMorgan owned smartphones and their transcripts of digitally recorded phone conversations to search, aggregate, sort, and analyze this information for any specific keywords, phrases, and patterns of behavior.<ref name=Bloomberg180419Waldman/><ref name=Bloomberg180419Mak/> In 2013, Cavicchia may have shared this information with [[Frank Bisignano]] who had become the CEO of [[First Data Corporation]].<ref name=Bloomberg180419Waldman/>\n\n===Other===\nThe company has been involved in a number of business and consumer products, designing in part or in whole. For example, in 2014, they premiered Insightics, which according to the ''[[Wall Street Journal]] '' \"extracts customer spending and demographic information from merchants\u2019 [[Credit history|credit-card records]].\" It was created in tandem with credit processing company [[First Data]].<ref name=\"tezfirstprofit\">\n{{cite news\n| title       =First Data Reports First Quarterly Profit in More Than Seven Years\n| first       =Robin\n| last        =Sidel\n| url         =https://www.wsj.com/articles/first-data-reports-first-quarterly-profit-in-more-than-seven-years-1423602902\n| newspaper   =[[Wall Street Journal]] \n| date        =February 10, 2015\n| accessdate  = 2015-02-25\n}}</ref>\n\n== Customers ==\n\n===Private civilian use===\n{{See also|Information Warfare Monitor}}\nPalantir Metropolis is used by hedge funds, banks, and financial services firms.<ref name=\"bare_url\" /><ref name=\"npr\" /><ref name=\"bare_url_a\">{{cite web| title=PayPal-Based Technology Helped Bust India's And The Dalai Lama's Cyberspies |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/firewall/2010/04/30/paypal-based-technology-helped-bust-indias-and-the-dalai-lamas-cyberspies/ | magazine=Forbes | first= Oliver | last=Chiang |date=2010-04-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gov2expo.com/gov2expo2010/public/schedule/detail/13996 |title=A Human Driven Data-centric Approach to Accountability: Analyzing Data to Prevent Fraud, Waste and Abuse in Stimulus Spending: Gov 2.0 Expo 2010 - Co-produced by UBM TechWeb & O'Reilly Conferences, May 25 - 27, 2010, Washington, DC |publisher=Gov2expo.com |date= |accessdate= 2012-01-30}}</ref>\n\nPalantir Foundry clients include Merck KGaA,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mobihealthnews.com/content/merck-kgaa-palantirs-new-joint-venture-looks-tear-down-cancer-research-data-silos|title=Merck KGaA, Palantir's new joint venture looks to tear down cancer research data silos|date=2018-11-20|website=MobiHealthNews|language=en|access-date=2019-02-27}}</ref> Airbus<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2018/10/22/airbus-believes-its-ai-can-eliminate-flight-delays/|title=Airbus believes its AI can eliminate flight delays|date=2018-10-23|website=VentureBeat|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-27}}</ref> and Ferrari.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/palantir-foundry-enables-scuderia-ferrari-through-data-873451908.html|title=Palantir Foundry Enables Scuderia Ferrari Through Data|last=Palantir|website=www.prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-27}}</ref>\n\nPalantir partner [[Information Warfare Monitor]] used Palantir software to uncover both the [[Ghostnet]] and the [[Shadow Network]].<ref name=\"bare_url_a\" /><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/video/#/video/tech/2009/03/30/vause.china.cyber.espionage.cnn | work=CNN | title=CNN.com Video}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/29/technology/29spy.html | work=The New York Times | title=Vast Spy System Loots Computers in 103 Countries | first=John | last=Markoff | date=March 29, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===U.S. civil entities===\nPalantir\u2019s software is used by the [[Recovery Accountability and Transparency Board]] to detect and investigate fraud and abuse in the [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act]].  Specifically, the Recovery Operations Center (ROC) used Palantir to integrate transactional data with open-source and private data sets that describe the entities receiving stimulus funds.{{clarify|date=March 2015}}<ref name=\"bare_url_b\" /> Other clients as of 2019 included [[Polaris Project]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.palantir.com/2014/01/how-many-years-a-slave/|title=How Many Years A Slave?|date=January 24, 2014|first=Karin|last=Knox|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304125053/https://www.palantir.com/2014/01/how-many-years-a-slave/|archive-date=March 4, 2016}}</ref> the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]], the [[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]],<ref name=\"tebtecnchrun\" /> the [[National Institutes of Health]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mobihealthnews.com/content/7m-contract-nih-taps-big-data-analysis-platform-palantir-streamline-health-research|title=With $7M contract, NIH taps big data analysis platform Palantir to streamline health research|date=2018-09-24|website=MobiHealthNews|language=en|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref> [[Team Rubicon]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2016/03/14/how-palantir-uses-big-data-to-find-missing-kids/|title=Can Data-Crunching Palantir Find Missing Children and Catch Traffickers?|website=Fortune|language=en|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref> and the United Nations [[World Food Programme]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www1.wfp.org/news/palantir-and-wfp-partner-help-transform-global-humanitarian-delivery|title=Palantir and WFP partner to help transform global humanitarian delivery {{!}} World Food Programme|website=www1.wfp.org|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref>\n\n===U.S. military, intelligence, and police===\nPalantir Gotham is used by counter-terrorism analysts at offices in the [[United States Intelligence Community]] and [[United States Department of Defense]], fraud investigators at the [[Recovery Accountability and Transparency Board]], and cyber analysts at [[Information Warfare Monitor]] (responsible for the [[GhostNet]] and the [[Shadow Network]] investigation).\n\nOther clients as of 2013 included [[DHS]], [[NSA]], [[FBI]], [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]], the [[United States Marine Corps|Marine Corps]], the [[United States Air Force|Air Force]], [[United States Special Operations Command|Special Operations Command]], [[West Point]], the [[Joint IED Defeat Organization]] and Allies. However, at the time the [[United States Army]] continued to use its own data analysis tool.<ref name=\"tebtecnchrun\"/> Also, according to [[TechCrunch]], \"The U.S. spy agencies also employed Palantir to [[database integration|connect databases]] across departments. Before this, most of the databases used by the CIA and [[FBI]] were [[Information silo|silo]]ed, forcing users to search each database individually. Now everything is linked together using Palantir.\"<ref name=\"tebtecnchrun\"/>\n\nU.S. [[military intelligence]] used the Palantir product to improve their ability to predict locations of [[improvised explosive devices]] in its [[war in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|war in Afghanistan]]. A small number of practitioners reported it to be more useful than the United States Army's program of record, the [[Distributed Common Ground System]] (DCGS-A). California Congressman [[Duncan D. Hunter]] complained of [[United States Department of Defense]] obstacles to its wider use in 2012.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper= [[The Washington Times]]  |title=Military has to fight to purchase lauded IED buster |date= July 16, 2012 |url= http://p.washingtontimes.com/news/2012/jul/16/military-has-to-fight-to-purchase-lauded-ied-buste/ |authorlink=Rowan Scarborough |first=Rowan |last =Scarborough |accessdate= September 29, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nPalantir has also been reported to be working with various U.S. police departments, for example accepting a contract in 2013 to help the Northern California Regional Intelligence Center build a controversial [[license plate]]s database for California.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/6/29/4478748/california-license-plate-reader-database-palantir|title=Palantir is helping California police develop controversial license plate database|first=Jeff|last=Blagdon|date=June 29, 2013|publisher=[[The Verge]]}}</ref> In 2012 [[New Orleans Police Department]] partnered with Palantir to create a predictive policing program.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/2/27/17054740/palantir-predictive-policing-tool-new-orleans-nopd |title=PALANTIR HAS SECRETLY BEEN USING NEW ORLEANS TO TEST ITS PREDICTIVE POLICING TECHNOLOGY |first=Ali |last=Winston |date = February 27, 2018 |publisher=[[The Verge]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, [[US Immigration and Customs Enforcement]] (ICE) awarded Palantir a $41 million contract to build and maintain a new intelligence system called Investigative Case Management (ICM) to track personal and criminal records of legal and [[illegal immigrant]]s. This application has originally been conceived by ICE's office of Homeland Security Investigations (HSI), allowing its users access to intelligence platforms maintained by other federal and private law enforcement entities. The system reached its \"final operation capacity\" under the Trump administration in September 2017.<ref>Woodman, Spencer (March 2017). [https://theintercept.com/2017/03/02/palantir-provides-the-engine-for-donald-trumps-deportation-machine/ \"Palantir Provides the Engine for Donald Trump\u2019s Deportation Machine\"]. ''TheIntercept_''. Retrieved 5 November 2018.</ref>\n\nPalantir took over the Pentagon's [[Project Maven]] contract in 2019 after Google decided not to continue developing the AI unmanned spy drone project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/palantir-took-over-from-google-on-project-maven-2019-12|title=Palantir took over from Google on Project Maven|last=|first=|date=December 2019|website=Business Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===International Atomic Energy Agency===\nPalantir has been pivotal for the [[International Atomic Energy Agency|International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA)]] to verify if Iran is in compliance with the [[Iran nuclear deal framework|2015 agreement]].<ref>{{cite news | last = Tirone | first = Jonathan | title = Peter Thiel and Palantir Are at the Heart of the Iran Nuclear Deal | access-date = May 8, 2018 | date = May 7, 2018 | url = https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-05-08/peter-thiel-in-eye-of-iran-storm-as-deadline-looms-for-trump | publisher = Bloomberg News}}</ref>\n\n== Palantir Night Live event==\nPalantir hosts Palantir Night Live at Palantir's McLean and Palo Alto offices. The event brings speakers from the intelligence community and technology space to discuss topics of common interest. Past speakers include [[Garry Kasparov]]; Nart Villeneuve from [[Information Warfare Monitor]]; [[Andrew McAfee]], author of Enterprise 2.0; [[Nelson Dellis]], memory athlete; and [[Michael Chertoff]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.washingtonlife.com/2010/04/09/society-2-0-tenet-chertoff-and-beer-oh-my/ |title=Society 2.0: Tenet, Chertoff and Beer, Oh My! &#124; Washington Life Magazine |publisher=Washingtonlife.com |date=2010-04-09 |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n\n===Algorithm development===\n[[i2 Limited|I2 Inc]] sued Palantir in Federal Court alleging fraud, conspiracy, and copyright infringement over Palantir's algorithm. Shyam Sankar, Palantir's director of business development, used a private eye company as the cutout for obtaining I2's code. I2 settled out of court for $10 million in 2011.<ref name=Bloomberg180419Waldman/>\n\n===WikiLeaks proposals (2010)===\nIn 2010 [[Hunton & Williams]] LLP allegedly asked [[Berico Technologies]], Palantir, and [[HBGary Federal]] to draft a response plan to \"the [[WikiLeaks]] Threat.\" In early 2011 [[Anonymous (group)|Anonymous]] publicly released HBGary-internal documents, including the plan. The plan proposed Palantir software would \"serve as the foundation for all the data collection, integration, analysis, and production efforts.\"<ref name=\"Harris\">{{cite web|last=Harris|first=Shane|title=Killer App|url=http://www.washingtonian.com/articles/people/killer-app/|work=Washingtonian|date=31 January 2012|accessdate=14 March 2012}}</ref>  The plan also included slides, allegedly authored by HBGary CEO Aaron Barr, which suggested \"[spreading] disinformation\" and \"disrupting\" [[Glenn Greenwald]]\u2019s support for WikiLeaks.<ref>{{cite web|first1=James|last1=Wray|first2=Ulf|last2=Stabe|url=http://www.thetechherald.com/articles/Data-intelligence-firms-proposed-a-systematic-attack-against-WikiLeaks/12751/ |title=Data intelligence firms proposed a systematic attack against WikiLeaks |publisher=Thetechherald.com |date= |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref>\n\nPalantir CEO Karp ended all ties to HBGary and issued a statement apologizing to \"progressive organizations\u2026 and Greenwald \u2026 for any involvement that we may have had in these matters.\" Palantir placed an employee on leave pending a review by a third-party law firm. The employee was later reinstated.<ref name=\"Harris\"/>\n\n===Racial discrimination lawsuit (2016)===\nOn September 26, 2016, the [[Office of Federal Contract Compliance Programs]] of the [[United States Department of Labor|U.S. Department of Labor]] filed a lawsuit against Palantir alleging that the company discriminated against Asian job applicants on the basis of their race.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dol.gov/sites/default/files/newsroom/newsreleases/OFCCP20160926_0.pdf|title=COMPLAINT FOR VIOLATIONS OF EXECUTIVE ORDER 11246|publisher=[[United States Department of Justice]]}}</ref> According to the lawsuit, the company \"routinely eliminated\" Asian applicants during the hiring process, even when they were \"as qualified as white applicants\" for the same jobs.<ref name=vanityfair>{{cite web|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/news/2016/09/us-government-sues-palantir-discrimination|title=U.S. GOVERNMENT SUES PETER THIEL\u2019S SECRETIVE BIG-DATA START-UP FOR DISCRIMINATION|website=Vanity Fair|first=Maya|last=Kosoff|date=September 27, 2016|accessdate=October 31, 2016}}</ref> Palantir settled the suit in April 2017 for $1.7 million while not admitting wrongdoing.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kravets|first1=David|title=Palantir settles US charges that it discriminated against Asian engineers|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2017/04/palantir-settles-us-charges-it-discriminated-against-asian-engineers/|accessdate=26 April 2017|publisher=Ars Technica|date=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===British Parliament Inquiry (2018)===\nDuring questioning in front of the digital, culture, media and sport select committee, [[Christopher Wylie]], the former research director of [[Cambridge Analytica]], said that several meetings had taken place between Palantir and Cambridge Analytica, and that Alexander Nix, the chief executive of [[SCL Group|SCL]], had facilitated their use of [[Aleksandr Kogan]]'s data which had been obtained from his app \"thisismydigitallife\" by mining personal surveys. Kogan later established Global Science Research to share the data with Cambridge Analytica and others. Wylie confirmed that both employees from Cambridge Analytica and Palantir used Kogan's Global Science Research data together in the same offices.<ref name=Guardian180327Pegg>{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/28/palantir-employee-cambridge-analytica | title = US data firm admits employee approached Cambridge Analytica: Palantir confirm employee \u2018engaged in a personal capacity\u2019 with the company | newspaper = The Guardian | date = March 27, 2018 | access-date = April 23, 2018 | last1 = Pegg | first1 = David | last2 = Cadwalladr | first2 = Carole | author-link2 = Carole Cadwalladr}}</ref><ref name=NYT180327>{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/27/us/cambridge-analytica-palantir.html | title = Spy Contractor\u2019s Idea Helped Cambridge Analytica Harvest Facebook Data | newspaper = New York Times | date = March 27, 2018 | access-date = April 24, 2018 | last1 = Confessore | first1 = Nicholas | last2 = Rosenberg | first2 = Matthew | author-link1 = Nicholas Confessore | author-link2 = Matthew Rosenberg}}</ref>\n\n===ICE Partnership (since 2014) ===\nPalantir has come under criticism due to its partnership developing software for [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement]]. Palantir has responded that its software is not used to facilitate deportations. In a statement provided to the New York Times,<ref>{{cite web |title=DealBook Briefing: Investors May Be Overlooking Their Own Discrimination |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/11/business/dealbook/investor-bias-discrimination.html |website=The New York Times |date=11 December 2018}}</ref> the firm implied that because its contract was with HSI, a division of ICE focused on investigating criminal activities, it played no role in deportations. However, documents obtained by The Intercept<ref>{{cite web |last1=Woodman |first1=Spencer |title=Palantir Provides the Engine for Donald Trump\u2019s Deportation Machine |url=https://theintercept.com/2017/03/02/palantir-provides-the-engine-for-donald-trumps-deportation-machine/ |website=The Intercept |publisher=The Intercept |date=2 March 2017}}</ref> show that this is not the case. According to these documents, Palantir's ICM software is considered 'mission critical' to ICE. Other groups critical of Palantir include the Brennan Center for Justice,<ref>{{cite web |title=Palantir Contract Dispute Exposes NYPD\u2019s Lack of Transparency |url=https://www.brennancenter.org/blog/palantir-contract-dispute-exposes-nypd%E2%80%99s-lack-transparency |website=Brennan Center for Justice |publisher=Brennan Center for Justice}}</ref> National Immigration Project,<ref>{{cite web |title=National Immigration Project of the National Lawyers Guild |url=https://www.nationalimmigrationproject.org/index.html |website=www.nationalimmigrationproject.org}}</ref> the Immigrant Defense Project,<ref>{{cite web |title=Immigrant Defense Project - Fighting for Justice & Human Rights for ALL |url=https://www.immigrantdefenseproject.org/}}</ref> the [[Tech Workers Coalition]] and Mijente.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mijente |url=https://mijente.net/notechforice/ |website=Mijente}}</ref> In one internal ICE report<ref>{{cite web |title=Palantir Played Key Role in Arresting Families for Deportation, Document Shows |url=https://mijente.net/2019/05/02/palantir-arresting-families/ |website=Mijente |date=2 May 2019}}</ref> Mijente acquired, it was revealed that Palantir's software was critical in an operation to arrest the parents of illegal migrant children.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Government by algorithm]]\n* [[Recorded Future]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"teafunding\">\n{{cite news\n| title       =Palantir Aiming To Raise $400 Million In New Round\n| first       =Ryan\n| last        =Mac\n| url         =https://www.forbes.com/sites/ryanmac/2014/12/11/palantir-aiming-to-raise-400-million-in-new-round/\n| newspaper   =[[Forbes]]\n| date        =December 11, 2014\n| accessdate  = 2015-02-21\n}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"tebtecnchrun\">\n{{cite news\n| title       =Leaked Palantir Doc Reveals Uses, Specific Functions And Key Clients\n| first       =Matt\n| last        =Burns\n| url         =https://techcrunch.com/2015/01/11/leaked-palantir-doc-reveals-uses-specific-functions-and-key-clients/\n| publisher   =[[TechCrunch]]\n| date        =January 11, 2015\n| accessdate  = 2015-02-21\n}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.palantir.com/ Palantir Technologies]\n\n[[Category:2003 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Big data companies]]\n[[Category:Business software companies]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Palo Alto, California]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 2003]]\n[[Category:Data brokers]]\n[[Category:Detectives and criminal investigators| ]]\n[[Category:Criminal investigation]]\n[[Category:Software companies based in the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Software companies of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Palantir Technologies Inc.\n| logo = Palantir company logo.png\n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| products = {{plainlist|\n*Palantir Gotham\n*Palantir Foundry}}\n| num_employees = {{increase}}2,500 (October 2019)<ref>{{cite news |first=Quentin |last=Hardy |date=May 31, 2014 |title = Unlocking Secrets, if Not Its Own Value |work = [[The New York Times]] |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/01/business/unlocking-secrets-if-not-its-own-value.html |accessdate = 2015-01-19}}</ref><ref name=20billion/>\n| foundation = {{start date and age|2003}}\n| founders = [[Peter Thiel]]<br>Nathan Gettings<br>[[Joe Lonsdale]]<br>[[Stephen Cohen (entrepreneur)|Stephen Cohen]]<br>[[Alex Karp]]\n| key_people = {{plainlist|\n*Peter Thiel ([[Chairman]])\n*Alex Karp ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])}}\n| location_city = [[Palo Alto, California]], US\n| revenue = $739 million (2019)<ref>{{cite news |title = Palantir revenue |work = Craft |url = https://www.businessinsider.com/palantir-1-billion-revenue-2020-ipo-2020-4|accessdate = 2019-11-20}}</ref>\n| homepage = {{url|http://www.palantir.com/}}\n}}\n'''Palantir Technologies''' is a [[privately held company|private]] American software company that specializes in [[big data]] [[analytics]]. Headquartered in [[Palo Alto, California]], it was founded by [[Peter Thiel]], Nathan Gettings, [[Joe Lonsdale]], [[Stephen Cohen (entrepreneur)|Stephen Cohen]], and [[Alex Karp]]. The company's name is derived from ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]'': a ''[[palant\u00edr]]'' is an artifact used to communicate with or see faraway parts of the world.\n\nThe company is known for three projects in particular: Palantir Gotham, Palantir Metropolis and Palantir Foundry. Palantir Gotham is used by [[counter-terrorism]] analysts at offices in the [[United States Intelligence Community]] (USIC) and [[United States Department of Defense]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-25/peter-thiel-s-palantir-wins-role-in-823-million-government-contract|title=Peter Thiel\u2019s Palantir Wins Role in $823 Million Government Contract|date=2020-02-25|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2020-03-18|language=en}}</ref>, fraud investigators at the [[Recovery Accountability and Transparency Board]], and cyber analysts at [[Information Warfare Monitor]], while Palantir Metropolis is used by [[Hedge fund|hedge funds]], banks, and financial services firms.<ref name=\"bare_url\" /><ref name=\"npr\" /> Palantir Foundry is used by corporate clients such as Morgan Stanley, Merck KGaA, Airbus, and Fiat Chrysler Automobiles NV.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=b07a6000-3595-11e9-8c0f-aba472ef73fe&url=L25ld3MvYXJ0aWNsZXMvMjAxOS0wMS0xNi9wYWxhbnRpci1wb3N0ZWQtbmVhcmx5LTEtYmlsbGlvbi1pbi0yMDE4LXNhbGVzLWV4ZWN1dGl2ZS1zYXlz|title=Bloomberg - Are you a robot?|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2019-02-21}}</ref> Palantir's original clients were federal agencies of the USIC. It has since expanded its customer base to serve state and local governments, as well as private companies in the financial and healthcare industries.<ref name=\"historypalantir\"/> Karp, Palantir's [[chief executive officer]], announced in 2013 that the company would not pursue an [[IPO]], as going public would make \"running a company like ours very difficult\".<ref name=\"teafunding\"/> However, on October 18, 2018, the [[Wall Street Journal]] reported that Palantir was considering an IPO in the first half of 2019 following a $41 billion valuation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/secretive-data-company-palantir-weighs-giant-public-offering-1539864003|title=Secretive Data Company Palantir Weighs Giant Public Offering|last=Copeland|first=Rob|date=2018-10-18|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2018-10-19|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\nThe company was valued at $9 billion in early 2014, with ''[[Forbes]]'' stating that the valuation made Palantir \"among [[Silicon Valley]]'s most valuable private technology companies\".<ref name=\"teafunding\"/> As of December 2014, Thiel was Palantir's largest shareholder.<ref name=\"teafunding\"/> In January 2015, the company was valued at $15 billion after an undisclosed round of funding with $50 million in November 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|title = SEC FORM D |url = https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1321655/000132165514000005/xslFormDX01/primary_doc.xml |publisher=[[Securities and Exchange Commission]] |accessdate = 2015-05-31}}</ref> This valuation rose to $20 billion in late 2015 as the company closed an $880 million round of funding.<ref name=20billion>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/12/23/palantir-has-raised-880-million-at-a-20-billion-valuation/|title=Palantir Has Raised $880 Million At A $20 Billion Valuation|first=Sarah|last=Buhr|website=[[TechCrunch]]|date=December 23, 2015}}</ref> Palantir has never reported a profit. In 2018, [[Morgan Stanley]] valued the company at $6 billion.<ref>{{cite web|title=Palantir Knows Everything About You|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/features/2018-palantir-peter-thiel/?ncid=newsltushpmgnews__TheMorningEmail__042018|website=Bloomberg|accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n===2003\u20132008: Founding and early years===\n[[File:Peter Thiel TechCrunch50.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Founder and chairman [[Peter Thiel]] was Palantir's largest shareholder as of late 2014.]]\nThough usually listed as having been founded in 2004, [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission|SEC]] filings state Palantir's official incorporation to be in May 2003 by [[Peter Thiel]] (co-founder of [[PayPal]]), who named the start-up after the \"[[Palant\u00edr|seeing stone]]\" in [[Tolkien's legendarium]].<ref name=\"historypalantir\">{{cite web |title=A (Pretty) Complete History of Palantir |publisher=Maus Strategic Consulting |url=http://www.mausstrategicconsulting.com/1/post/2014/04/a-pretty-complete-history-of-palantir.html |date=April 2014 |archivedate=16 May 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140516035733/http://www.mausstrategicconsulting.com/1/post/2014/04/a-pretty-complete-history-of-palantir.html |url-status=dead}}</ref> Thiel saw Palantir as a \"mission-oriented company\" which could apply software similar to PayPal's fraud recognition systems to \"reduce terrorism while preserving civil liberties.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Greenberg|first1=Andy|last2=Mac|first2=Ryan|title=How A 'Deviant' Philosopher Built Palantir, A CIA-Funded Data-Mining Juggernaut|website=Forbes|date=August 14, 2013|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andygreenberg/2013/08/14/agent-of-intelligence-how-a-deviant-philosopher-built-palantir-a-cia-funded-data-mining-juggernaut/}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Thiel bankrolled the creation of a prototype by PayPal engineer Nathan Gettings and [[Stanford University]] students [[Joe Lonsdale]] and [[Stephen Cohen (entrepreneur)|Stephen Cohen]]. That same year, Thiel hired [[Alex Karp]], a former colleague of his from [[Stanford Law School]], as [[chief executive officer]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://media.palantirtech.com/videos/charlierose.html |title=charlierose |publisher= Media.palantirtech.com |date= |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.crunchbase.com/company/palantir-technologies |title= Palantir Technologies &#124; CrunchBase Profile |publisher=Crunchbase.com |date= |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref>\n\nHeadquartered in [[Palo Alto, California]], the company initially struggled to find investors. According to Karp, [[Sequoia Capital]] chairman [[Michael Moritz]] doodled through an entire meeting, and a [[Kleiner Perkins]] executive lectured the founders about the inevitable failure of their company.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.palantir.com/contact |title= Contact information}}</ref> The only early investments were $2 million from the U.S. [[Central Intelligence Agency]]'s venture capital arm [[In-Q-Tel]], and $30 million from Thiel himself and his venture capital firm, [[Founders Fund]].<ref name=\"bare_url\">{{cite news| url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB125200842406984303 | work=The Wall Street Journal | title=How Team of Geeks Cracked Spy Trade | first=Siobhan | last=Gorman | date=September 4, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"npr\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=106479613 |title= A Tech Fix For Illegal Government Snooping? |publisher=NPR |date= |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foundersfund.com/palantir.php |title=Palantir |publisher= Founders Fund | accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Evelyn |last=Rusli |url=https://techcrunch.com/2010/06/25/palantir-the-next-billion-dollar-company-raises-90-million/ |title=Palantir: The Next Billion-Dollar Company Raises $90 Million |publisher=TechCrunch |date=2010-06-25 |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref><ref name=\"charlierose\">{{cite web|url=http://www.charlierose.com/guest/view/6717 |title= Alexander Karp |publisher=Charlie Rose |date=2009-08-11 |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref>\n\nPalantir developed its technology by computer scientists and analysts from intelligence agencies over three years, through pilots facilitated by In-Q-Tel.<ref>{{cite web| first =Jeff | last = Widman |url= https://venturebeat.com/2009/06/05/palantir-keeps-it-lean-and-mean-on-five-year-journey-from-zero-to-150-employees/ |title=Palantir keeps it lean and mean on five-year journey from zero to 150 employees | publisher=VentureBeat |date=2009-06-05 |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref><ref name=\"bare_url\" /> The company stated computers alone using [[artificial intelligence]] could not defeat an adaptive adversary. Instead, Palantir proposed using human analysts to explore data from many sources, called [[Intelligence amplification|intelligence augmentation]].<ref>{{cite web| first =Ari | last = Gesher |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120414224548/http://blog.palantirtech.com/2010/03/08/friction-in-human-computer-symbiosis-kasparov-on-chess/ |title= Friction in Human-Computer Symbiosis: Kasparov on Chess |publisher= Palantir tech |date=2010-03-08 |accessdate= 2012-01-30}}</ref>\n\n===2009: GhostNet and the Shadow Network ===\nIn 2009 and 2010 respectively, [[Information Warfare Monitor]] used Palantir software to uncover the [[GhostNet]] and the [[Shadow Network]]. The GhostNet was a China-based cyber espionage network targeting  1,295 computers in 103 countries, including the [[Dalai Lama]]\u2019s office, a [[NATO]] computer and  various national embassies.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.cnn.com/video/#/video/tech/2009/03/30/vause.china.cyber.espionage.cnn | work=CNN | title= Video}}</ref> The Shadow Network was also a China-based espionage operation that hacked into the Indian security and defense apparatus. Cyber spies stole documents related to Indian security and NATO troop activity in Afghanistan.<ref name=\"bare_url_a\" /><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/29/technology/29spy.html | work=The New York Times | title=Vast Spy System Loots Computers in 103 Countries | first= John | last=Markoff | date=March 29, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===2010\u20132012: Expansion===\nIn April 2010, Palantir announced a partnership with [[Thomson Reuters]] to sell the Palantir Metropolis product as QA Studio.<ref>{{cite news| title=Press release: Thomson Reuters and Palantir Technologies enter exclusive agreement to create next-generation analytics platform for financial clients |url= http://thomsonreuters.com/content/press_room/financial/2010_04_12_palantir_technologies_agreement |date=2010-04-12 |publisher= Thomson Reuters}}</ref>\nOn June 18, 2010, [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Joe Biden]] and [[Office of Management and Budget]] Director [[Peter Orszag]] held a press conference at the White House announcing the success of fighting fraud in the stimulus by the [[Recovery Accountability and Transparency Board]] (RATB).  Biden credited the success to the software, Palantir, being deployed by the federal government.<ref>{{cite web|first=Tim |last=Kauffman | url=http://www.federaltimes.com/article/20100627/AGENCY05/6270306/ |title=The new high-tech weapons against fraud |publisher= Federal Times |date=2010-06-27 |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref>  He announced that the capability will be deployed at other government agencies, starting with [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]] and [[Medicaid]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/theoval/post/2010/06/obama-administration-to-create-do-not-pay-list-to-bar-shady-contractors/1 | newspaper=USA Today | title=Obama administration to create 'do not pay' list to bar shady contractors | date=2010-06-18 | first=Kathy | last=Kiely}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Peter |last=Orszag |url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/omb/blog/10/06/18/Do-Not-Pay-Do-Read-This-Post|title=Do Not Pay? Do Read This Post |publisher=Whitehouse.gov |date=2010-06-18 |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref><ref name=\"bare_url_b\">{{cite news| url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2010/06/01/companies-capitalize-on-open-government |work= Political Ticker blog |first= Eric |last= Kuhn |date= June 1, 2010 | publisher=CNN | title=Companies capitalize on 'open government' |accessdate= September 28, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.palantir.com/2010/05/govcon5-videos-now-available/ |title=Using Palantir with Open Source Data: Finding and Preventing Fraud in Stimulus Spending |publisher=Palantir Technologies |date=2010-05-04}}</ref>\n\nEstimates were $250 million in revenues in 2011.<ref>{{Cite news |title= Palantir, the War on Terror's Secret Weapon: A Silicon Valley startup that collates threats has quietly become indispensable to the U.S. intelligence community |work= Business Week Magazine |date= November 22, 2011 |first1= Ashlee |last1=Vance |first2=Brad |last2=Stone |url= http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/palantir-the-vanguard-of-cyberterror-security-11222011.html |accessdate= September 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2013\u20132016: Additional funding===\n{|class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float: right; margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 0em; font-size: 85%; background:offwhite; color:black; width:30em; max-width: 60%;\" cellspacing=\"5\"\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|\"[As of 2013] the U.S. spy agencies also employed Palantir to connect databases across departments. Before this, most of the databases used by the CIA and FBI were [[Information silo|siloed]], forcing users to search each database individually. Now everything is linked together using Palantir.\"\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|\u2014 [[TechCrunch]] in January 2015<ref name=\"tebtecnchrun\"/>\n|}\nA document leaked to [[TechCrunch]] revealed that Palantir's clients as of 2013 included at least twelve groups within the U.S. government, including the [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]], [[United States Department of Homeland Security|DHS]], [[National Security Agency|NSA]], [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]], [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]], the [[United States Marine Corps|Marine Corps]], the [[United States Air Force|Air Force]], [[United States Special Operations Command|Special Operations Command]], [[West Point]], the [[Joint Improvised-Threat Defeat Organization]] and Allies, the [[Recovery Accountability and Transparency Board]] and the [[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]. However, at the time the [[United States Army]] continued to use its own data analysis tool.<ref name= \"tebtecnchrun\"/> Also, according to [[TechCrunch]], the U.S. spy agencies such as the CIA and FBI were linked for the first time with Palantir software, as their databases had previously been \"[[Information silo|siloed]].\"<ref name= \"tebtecnchrun\" />\n\nIn September 2013, Palantir disclosed over $196 million in funding according to a U.S. [[Securities and Exchange Commission]] filing.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1321655/000132165513000002/xslFormDX01/primary_doc.xml | title = Notice of Exempt Offering of Securities |date= September 27, 2013 | accessdate = September 28, 2013 | publisher = The United States Securities and Exchange Commission}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Cutler|first=Kim-Mai|title=Palantir Is Raising $197M In Growth Capital, SEC Filing Shows |url= https://techcrunch.com/2013/09/27/palantir-197m-sec-filing/|publisher=TechCrunch}}</ref> It was estimated that the company would likely close almost $1 billion in contracts in 2014.<ref>{{cite news | first1 = Andy | last1 = Greenberg | first2 = Ryan | last2 = Mac | title = How A 'Deviant' Philosopher Built Palantir, A CIA-Funded Data-Mining Juggernaut | date = September 2, 2013 | url = https://www.forbes.com/sites/andygreenberg/2013/08/14/agent-of-intelligence-how-a-deviant-philosopher-built-palantir-a-cia-funded-data-mining-juggernaut/ | work = Forbes | accessdate = September 28, 2013}}</ref> CEO [[Alex Karp]] announced in 2013 that the company would not be pursuing an [[IPO]], as going public would make \"running a company like ours very difficult.\"<ref name=\"teafunding\"/> In December 2013, the company began a round of financing, raising around $450 million from private funders.  This raised the company's value to $9 billion, according to ''[[Forbes]]'', with the magazine further explaining that the valuation made Palantir \"among Silicon Valley\u2019s most valuable private technology companies.\"<ref name= \"teafunding\" />\n\nIn December 2014, ''Forbes'' reported that Palantir was looking to raise $400 million in an additional round of financing, after the company filed paperwork with the [[Securities and Exchange Commission]] the month before. The report was based on research by VC Experts.  If completed, ''Forbes'' stated Palantir's funding could reach a total of $1.2 billion.<ref name=\"teafunding\"/> As of December 2014, the company continued to have diverse private funders, [[Kenneth Langone]] and [[Stanley Druckenmiller]], [[In-Q-Tel]] of the CIA,<ref>{{cite news|first= Jonathan |last= Tirone |date=2018-05-08|title=Peter Thiel and Palantir Are at the Heart of the Iran Nuclear Deal|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-05-08/peter-thiel-in-eye-of-iran-storm-as-deadline-looms-for-trump|newspaper=Bloomberg.com|quote=Palantir, which Thiel and his partners built with CIA funding}}</ref> Tiger Global Management, and [[Founders Fund]], which is a venture Firm operated by [[Peter Thiel]], the chairman of Palantir. As of December 2014, Thiel was Palantir's largest shareholder.<ref name=\"teafunding\" />\n\nThe company was valued at $15 billion in November 2014.<ref>{{Citation | date = Jan 16, 2015 | title = Palantir raising more money after tagged with 15 billion valuation | newspaper = The Wall Street Journal | url = https://blogs.wsj.com/digits/2015/01/16/palantir-raising-more-money-after-tagged-with-15-billion-valuation/}}.</ref> In June 2015, Buzzfeed reported the company was raising up to $500 million in new capital at a valuation of $20 billion.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.buzzfeed.com/williamalden/palantir-valued-at-20-billion-in-new-funding-round |title= Palantir Valued At $20 Billion In New Funding Round| first =William | last = Alden|date=June 23, 2015|publisher=[[Buzzfeed]]|accessdate=June 23, 2015}}</ref> By December 2015, it had raised a further $880 million, while the company was still valued at $20 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/12/23/palantir-has-raised-880-million-at-a-20-billion-valuation/|title=Palantir Has Raised $880 Million At A $20 Billion Valuation|date=December 23, 2015|first=Sarah|last=Buhr|publisher=[[TechCrunch]]}}</ref> In February 2016, Palantir bought Kimono Labs, a startup which makes it easy to collect information from public facing websites.\n\nIn August 2016, Palantir acquired [[data visualization]] startup Silk.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Condon|first1=Stephanie|title=Palantir acquires data visualization startup Silk|url=http://www.zdnet.com/article/palantir-acquires-data-visualization-startup-silk/|accessdate=10 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nPalantir, is one of four large technology firms <ref>{{Cite news|last=Kelion|first=Leo|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-52079287|title=NHS turns to big tech to tackle Covid-19 hot spots|date=2020-03-28|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-29|language=en-GB}}</ref>to start working with the NHS on supporting the [[COVID-19]] efforts through the provision of software from Palantir Foundry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://healthtech.blog.gov.uk/2020/03/28/the-power-of-data-in-a-pandemic/|title=The power of data in a pandemic - Technology in the NHS|website=healthtech.blog.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> \n\n== Products ==\n\n=== Palantir Gotham ===\nPalantir Gotham (formerly known as Palantir Government) [[data integration|integrates]] structured and [[unstructured data]], provides search and discovery capabilities, knowledge management, and secure collaboration. The Palantir platform includes the privacy and [[civil liberties]] protections mandated by legal requirements such as those in the [[9/11 Commission Implementation Act of 2004]].  Palantir's [[privacy]] controls purportedly keep investigations focused, as opposed to the expansive [[data mining]] techniques that have drawn criticism from privacy advocates concerned about civil liberties protection. Palantir maintains security tags{{explain|date=May 2016}} at a granular level.<ref name=\"npr\" /><ref name=\"charlierose\" />\n\nPalantir previously ran the site AnalyzeThe.US,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://analyzethe.us |title= AnalyzeThe.US \u2014 Home |work= Web site |publisher= Palantir  |accessdate= September 28, 2013 }}</ref> which allowed potential Palantir customers and affiliates to use Palantir Gotham to perform analysis on publicly available data from [[data.gov]], [[usaspending.gov]], the [[Center for Responsive Politics]]\u2019 Open Secrets Database, and Community Health Data from [[U.S. Department of Health & Human Services|hhs.gov]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fiercehealthcare.com/press-releases/palantir-technologies-showcase-analysis-community-health-data-initiative-forum-harnes |title=Palantir Technologies to Showcase Analysis at the Community Health Data Initiative Forum: Harnessing the Power of Information to |publisher=FierceHealthcare |date=2010-06-02 |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref>\n\n=== Palantir Metropolis ===\nPalantir Metropolis (formerly known as Palantir Finance) was<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-01-07/palantir-is-said-to-hire-salespeople-it-once-mocked-as-ipo-nears|title=Palantir Stops Mocking Salespeople and Starts Hiring Them|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-palantir-sales-ipo-20190107-story.html|title=Palantir once mocked the idea of salespeople. Now it\u2019s hiring them|last=Chapman|first=Lizette|website=latimes.com|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref> software for [[data integration]], [[information management]] and quantitative [[analytics]].  The software connects to commercial, proprietary and [[public data]] sets and discovers trends, relationships and anomalies, including [[predictive analytics]].<ref name=Bloomberg180419Waldman>{{cite news | last1 = Waldman | first1 = Peter | last2 = Chapman | first2 = Lizette | last3 = Robertson | first3 = Jordan | url = https://www.bloomberg.com/features/2018-palantir-peter-thiel/ | title = Peter Thiel\u2019s data-mining company is using War on Terror tools to track American citizens. The scary thing? Palantir is desperate for new customers. | publisher = Bloomberg | date = April 19, 2018 | access-date = April 24, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Bloomberg180419Mak>{{cite news | last = Mak | first = Aaron | title = Report: Palantir Helped JPMorgan Spy on Employees | url = https://slate.com/technology/2018/04/jpmorgan-used-palantir-tools-monitor-employee-activity-bloomberg-report.html | publisher = Bloomberg | date = April 19, 2018 | access-date = April 24, 2018}}</ref> Aided by 120 \"forward-deployed engineers\" of Palantir during 2009, Peter Cavicchia III of JPMorgan used Metropolis to monitor employee communications and alert the insider threat team when an employee showed any signs of potential disgruntlement: the insider alert team would further scrutinize the employee and possibly conduct physical surveillance after hours with bank security personnel.<ref name=Bloomberg180419Waldman/><ref name=Bloomberg180419Mak/> The Metropolis team used emails, download activity, browser histories, and GPS locations from JPMorgan owned smartphones and their transcripts of digitally recorded phone conversations to search, aggregate, sort, and analyze this information for any specific keywords, phrases, and patterns of behavior.<ref name=Bloomberg180419Waldman/><ref name=Bloomberg180419Mak/> In 2013, Cavicchia may have shared this information with [[Frank Bisignano]] who had become the CEO of [[First Data Corporation]].<ref name=Bloomberg180419Waldman/>\n\n===Other===\nThe company has been involved in a number of business and consumer products, designing in part or in whole. For example, in 2014, they premiered Insightics, which according to the ''[[Wall Street Journal]] '' \"extracts customer spending and demographic information from merchants\u2019 [[Credit history|credit-card records]].\" It was created in tandem with credit processing company [[First Data]].<ref name=\"tezfirstprofit\">\n{{cite news\n| title       =First Data Reports First Quarterly Profit in More Than Seven Years\n| first       =Robin\n| last        =Sidel\n| url         =https://www.wsj.com/articles/first-data-reports-first-quarterly-profit-in-more-than-seven-years-1423602902\n| newspaper   =[[Wall Street Journal]] \n| date        =February 10, 2015\n| accessdate  = 2015-02-25\n}}</ref>\n\n== Customers ==\n\n===Private civilian use===\n{{See also|Information Warfare Monitor}}\nPalantir Metropolis is used by hedge funds, banks, and financial services firms.<ref name=\"bare_url\" /><ref name=\"npr\" /><ref name=\"bare_url_a\">{{cite web| title=PayPal-Based Technology Helped Bust India's And The Dalai Lama's Cyberspies |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/firewall/2010/04/30/paypal-based-technology-helped-bust-indias-and-the-dalai-lamas-cyberspies/ | magazine=Forbes | first= Oliver | last=Chiang |date=2010-04-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gov2expo.com/gov2expo2010/public/schedule/detail/13996 |title=A Human Driven Data-centric Approach to Accountability: Analyzing Data to Prevent Fraud, Waste and Abuse in Stimulus Spending: Gov 2.0 Expo 2010 - Co-produced by UBM TechWeb & O'Reilly Conferences, May 25 - 27, 2010, Washington, DC |publisher=Gov2expo.com |date= |accessdate= 2012-01-30}}</ref>\n\nPalantir Foundry clients include Merck KGaA,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mobihealthnews.com/content/merck-kgaa-palantirs-new-joint-venture-looks-tear-down-cancer-research-data-silos|title=Merck KGaA, Palantir's new joint venture looks to tear down cancer research data silos|date=2018-11-20|website=MobiHealthNews|language=en|access-date=2019-02-27}}</ref> Airbus<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2018/10/22/airbus-believes-its-ai-can-eliminate-flight-delays/|title=Airbus believes its AI can eliminate flight delays|date=2018-10-23|website=VentureBeat|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-27}}</ref> and Ferrari.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/palantir-foundry-enables-scuderia-ferrari-through-data-873451908.html|title=Palantir Foundry Enables Scuderia Ferrari Through Data|last=Palantir|website=www.prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-27}}</ref>\n\nPalantir partner [[Information Warfare Monitor]] used Palantir software to uncover both the [[Ghostnet]] and the [[Shadow Network]].<ref name=\"bare_url_a\" /><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/video/#/video/tech/2009/03/30/vause.china.cyber.espionage.cnn | work=CNN | title=CNN.com Video}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/29/technology/29spy.html | work=The New York Times | title=Vast Spy System Loots Computers in 103 Countries | first=John | last=Markoff | date=March 29, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===U.S. civil entities===\nPalantir\u2019s software is used by the [[Recovery Accountability and Transparency Board]] to detect and investigate fraud and abuse in the [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act]].  Specifically, the Recovery Operations Center (ROC) used Palantir to integrate transactional data with open-source and private data sets that describe the entities receiving stimulus funds.{{clarify|date=March 2015}}<ref name=\"bare_url_b\" /> Other clients as of 2019 included [[Polaris Project]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.palantir.com/2014/01/how-many-years-a-slave/|title=How Many Years A Slave?|date=January 24, 2014|first=Karin|last=Knox|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304125053/https://www.palantir.com/2014/01/how-many-years-a-slave/|archive-date=March 4, 2016}}</ref> the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]], the [[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]],<ref name=\"tebtecnchrun\" /> the [[National Institutes of Health]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mobihealthnews.com/content/7m-contract-nih-taps-big-data-analysis-platform-palantir-streamline-health-research|title=With $7M contract, NIH taps big data analysis platform Palantir to streamline health research|date=2018-09-24|website=MobiHealthNews|language=en|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref> [[Team Rubicon]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2016/03/14/how-palantir-uses-big-data-to-find-missing-kids/|title=Can Data-Crunching Palantir Find Missing Children and Catch Traffickers?|website=Fortune|language=en|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref> and the United Nations [[World Food Programme]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www1.wfp.org/news/palantir-and-wfp-partner-help-transform-global-humanitarian-delivery|title=Palantir and WFP partner to help transform global humanitarian delivery {{!}} World Food Programme|website=www1.wfp.org|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref>\n\n===U.S. military, intelligence, and police===\nPalantir Gotham is used by counter-terrorism analysts at offices in the [[United States Intelligence Community]] and [[United States Department of Defense]], fraud investigators at the [[Recovery Accountability and Transparency Board]], and cyber analysts at [[Information Warfare Monitor]] (responsible for the [[GhostNet]] and the [[Shadow Network]] investigation).\n\nOther clients as of 2013 included [[DHS]], [[NSA]], [[FBI]], [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]], the [[United States Marine Corps|Marine Corps]], the [[United States Air Force|Air Force]], [[United States Special Operations Command|Special Operations Command]], [[West Point]], the [[Joint IED Defeat Organization]] and Allies. However, at the time the [[United States Army]] continued to use its own data analysis tool.<ref name=\"tebtecnchrun\"/> Also, according to [[TechCrunch]], \"The U.S. spy agencies also employed Palantir to [[database integration|connect databases]] across departments. Before this, most of the databases used by the CIA and [[FBI]] were [[Information silo|silo]]ed, forcing users to search each database individually. Now everything is linked together using Palantir.\"<ref name=\"tebtecnchrun\"/>\n\nU.S. [[military intelligence]] used the Palantir product to improve their ability to predict locations of [[improvised explosive devices]] in its [[war in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|war in Afghanistan]]. A small number of practitioners reported it to be more useful than the United States Army's program of record, the [[Distributed Common Ground System]] (DCGS-A). California Congressman [[Duncan D. Hunter]] complained of [[United States Department of Defense]] obstacles to its wider use in 2012.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper= [[The Washington Times]]  |title=Military has to fight to purchase lauded IED buster |date= July 16, 2012 |url= http://p.washingtontimes.com/news/2012/jul/16/military-has-to-fight-to-purchase-lauded-ied-buste/ |authorlink=Rowan Scarborough |first=Rowan |last =Scarborough |accessdate= September 29, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nPalantir has also been reported to be working with various U.S. police departments, for example accepting a contract in 2013 to help the Northern California Regional Intelligence Center build a controversial [[license plate]]s database for California.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/6/29/4478748/california-license-plate-reader-database-palantir|title=Palantir is helping California police develop controversial license plate database|first=Jeff|last=Blagdon|date=June 29, 2013|publisher=[[The Verge]]}}</ref> In 2012 [[New Orleans Police Department]] partnered with Palantir to create a predictive policing program.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/2/27/17054740/palantir-predictive-policing-tool-new-orleans-nopd |title=PALANTIR HAS SECRETLY BEEN USING NEW ORLEANS TO TEST ITS PREDICTIVE POLICING TECHNOLOGY |first=Ali |last=Winston |date = February 27, 2018 |publisher=[[The Verge]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, [[US Immigration and Customs Enforcement]] (ICE) awarded Palantir a $41 million contract to build and maintain a new intelligence system called Investigative Case Management (ICM) to track personal and criminal records of legal and [[illegal immigrant]]s. This application has originally been conceived by ICE's office of Homeland Security Investigations (HSI), allowing its users access to intelligence platforms maintained by other federal and private law enforcement entities. The system reached its \"final operation capacity\" under the Trump administration in September 2017.<ref>Woodman, Spencer (March 2017). [https://theintercept.com/2017/03/02/palantir-provides-the-engine-for-donald-trumps-deportation-machine/ \"Palantir Provides the Engine for Donald Trump\u2019s Deportation Machine\"]. ''TheIntercept_''. Retrieved 5 November 2018.</ref>\n\nPalantir took over the Pentagon's [[Project Maven]] contract in 2019 after Google decided not to continue developing the AI unmanned spy drone project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/palantir-took-over-from-google-on-project-maven-2019-12|title=Palantir took over from Google on Project Maven|last=|first=|date=December 2019|website=Business Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===International Atomic Energy Agency===\nPalantir has been pivotal for the [[International Atomic Energy Agency|International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA)]] to verify if Iran is in compliance with the [[Iran nuclear deal framework|2015 agreement]].<ref>{{cite news | last = Tirone | first = Jonathan | title = Peter Thiel and Palantir Are at the Heart of the Iran Nuclear Deal | access-date = May 8, 2018 | date = May 7, 2018 | url = https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-05-08/peter-thiel-in-eye-of-iran-storm-as-deadline-looms-for-trump | publisher = Bloomberg News}}</ref>\n\n== Palantir Night Live event==\nPalantir hosts Palantir Night Live at Palantir's McLean and Palo Alto offices. The event brings speakers from the intelligence community and technology space to discuss topics of common interest. Past speakers include [[Garry Kasparov]]; Nart Villeneuve from [[Information Warfare Monitor]]; [[Andrew McAfee]], author of Enterprise 2.0; [[Nelson Dellis]], memory athlete; and [[Michael Chertoff]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.washingtonlife.com/2010/04/09/society-2-0-tenet-chertoff-and-beer-oh-my/ |title=Society 2.0: Tenet, Chertoff and Beer, Oh My! &#124; Washington Life Magazine |publisher=Washingtonlife.com |date=2010-04-09 |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n\n===Algorithm development===\n[[i2 Limited|I2 Inc]] sued Palantir in Federal Court alleging fraud, conspiracy, and copyright infringement over Palantir's algorithm. Shyam Sankar, Palantir's director of business development, used a private eye company as the cutout for obtaining I2's code. I2 settled out of court for $10 million in 2011.<ref name=Bloomberg180419Waldman/>\n\n===WikiLeaks proposals (2010)===\nIn 2010 [[Hunton & Williams]] LLP allegedly asked [[Berico Technologies]], Palantir, and [[HBGary Federal]] to draft a response plan to \"the [[WikiLeaks]] Threat.\" In early 2011 [[Anonymous (group)|Anonymous]] publicly released HBGary-internal documents, including the plan. The plan proposed Palantir software would \"serve as the foundation for all the data collection, integration, analysis, and production efforts.\"<ref name=\"Harris\">{{cite web|last=Harris|first=Shane|title=Killer App|url=http://www.washingtonian.com/articles/people/killer-app/|work=Washingtonian|date=31 January 2012|accessdate=14 March 2012}}</ref>  The plan also included slides, allegedly authored by HBGary CEO Aaron Barr, which suggested \"[spreading] disinformation\" and \"disrupting\" [[Glenn Greenwald]]\u2019s support for WikiLeaks.<ref>{{cite web|first1=James|last1=Wray|first2=Ulf|last2=Stabe|url=http://www.thetechherald.com/articles/Data-intelligence-firms-proposed-a-systematic-attack-against-WikiLeaks/12751/ |title=Data intelligence firms proposed a systematic attack against WikiLeaks |publisher=Thetechherald.com |date= |accessdate=2012-01-30}}</ref>\n\nPalantir CEO Karp ended all ties to HBGary and issued a statement apologizing to \"progressive organizations\u2026 and Greenwald \u2026 for any involvement that we may have had in these matters.\" Palantir placed an employee on leave pending a review by a third-party law firm. The employee was later reinstated.<ref name=\"Harris\"/>\n\n===Racial discrimination lawsuit (2016)===\nOn September 26, 2016, the [[Office of Federal Contract Compliance Programs]] of the [[United States Department of Labor|U.S. Department of Labor]] filed a lawsuit against Palantir alleging that the company discriminated against Asian job applicants on the basis of their race.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dol.gov/sites/default/files/newsroom/newsreleases/OFCCP20160926_0.pdf|title=COMPLAINT FOR VIOLATIONS OF EXECUTIVE ORDER 11246|publisher=[[United States Department of Justice]]}}</ref> According to the lawsuit, the company \"routinely eliminated\" Asian applicants during the hiring process, even when they were \"as qualified as white applicants\" for the same jobs.<ref name=vanityfair>{{cite web|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/news/2016/09/us-government-sues-palantir-discrimination|title=U.S. GOVERNMENT SUES PETER THIEL\u2019S SECRETIVE BIG-DATA START-UP FOR DISCRIMINATION|website=Vanity Fair|first=Maya|last=Kosoff|date=September 27, 2016|accessdate=October 31, 2016}}</ref> Palantir settled the suit in April 2017 for $1.7 million while not admitting wrongdoing.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kravets|first1=David|title=Palantir settles US charges that it discriminated against Asian engineers|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2017/04/palantir-settles-us-charges-it-discriminated-against-asian-engineers/|accessdate=26 April 2017|publisher=Ars Technica|date=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===British Parliament Inquiry (2018)===\nDuring questioning in front of the digital, culture, media and sport select committee, [[Christopher Wylie]], the former research director of [[Cambridge Analytica]], said that several meetings had taken place between Palantir and Cambridge Analytica, and that Alexander Nix, the chief executive of [[SCL Group|SCL]], had facilitated their use of [[Aleksandr Kogan]]'s data which had been obtained from his app \"thisismydigitallife\" by mining personal surveys. Kogan later established Global Science Research to share the data with Cambridge Analytica and others. Wylie confirmed that both employees from Cambridge Analytica and Palantir used Kogan's Global Science Research data together in the same offices.<ref name=Guardian180327Pegg>{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/28/palantir-employee-cambridge-analytica | title = US data firm admits employee approached Cambridge Analytica: Palantir confirm employee \u2018engaged in a personal capacity\u2019 with the company | newspaper = The Guardian | date = March 27, 2018 | access-date = April 23, 2018 | last1 = Pegg | first1 = David | last2 = Cadwalladr | first2 = Carole | author-link2 = Carole Cadwalladr}}</ref><ref name=NYT180327>{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/27/us/cambridge-analytica-palantir.html | title = Spy Contractor\u2019s Idea Helped Cambridge Analytica Harvest Facebook Data | newspaper = New York Times | date = March 27, 2018 | access-date = April 24, 2018 | last1 = Confessore | first1 = Nicholas | last2 = Rosenberg | first2 = Matthew | author-link1 = Nicholas Confessore | author-link2 = Matthew Rosenberg}}</ref>\n\n===ICE Partnership (since 2014) ===\nPalantir has come under criticism due to its partnership developing software for [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement]]. Palantir has responded that its software is not used to facilitate deportations. In a statement provided to the New York Times,<ref>{{cite web |title=DealBook Briefing: Investors May Be Overlooking Their Own Discrimination |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/11/business/dealbook/investor-bias-discrimination.html |website=The New York Times |date=11 December 2018}}</ref> the firm implied that because its contract was with HSI, a division of ICE focused on investigating criminal activities, it played no role in deportations. However, documents obtained by The Intercept<ref>{{cite web |last1=Woodman |first1=Spencer |title=Palantir Provides the Engine for Donald Trump\u2019s Deportation Machine |url=https://theintercept.com/2017/03/02/palantir-provides-the-engine-for-donald-trumps-deportation-machine/ |website=The Intercept |publisher=The Intercept |date=2 March 2017}}</ref> show that this is not the case. According to these documents, Palantir's ICM software is considered 'mission critical' to ICE. Other groups critical of Palantir include the Brennan Center for Justice,<ref>{{cite web |title=Palantir Contract Dispute Exposes NYPD\u2019s Lack of Transparency |url=https://www.brennancenter.org/blog/palantir-contract-dispute-exposes-nypd%E2%80%99s-lack-transparency |website=Brennan Center for Justice |publisher=Brennan Center for Justice}}</ref> National Immigration Project,<ref>{{cite web |title=National Immigration Project of the National Lawyers Guild |url=https://www.nationalimmigrationproject.org/index.html |website=www.nationalimmigrationproject.org}}</ref> the Immigrant Defense Project,<ref>{{cite web |title=Immigrant Defense Project - Fighting for Justice & Human Rights for ALL |url=https://www.immigrantdefenseproject.org/}}</ref> the [[Tech Workers Coalition]] and Mijente.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mijente |url=https://mijente.net/notechforice/ |website=Mijente}}</ref> In one internal ICE report<ref>{{cite web |title=Palantir Played Key Role in Arresting Families for Deportation, Document Shows |url=https://mijente.net/2019/05/02/palantir-arresting-families/ |website=Mijente |date=2 May 2019}}</ref> Mijente acquired, it was revealed that Palantir's software was critical in an operation to arrest the parents of illegal migrant children.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Recorded Future]]\n